  "local_port": 52774,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "I'm 4 years into my H1B, my GC is not yet started. If I apply GC through consulting company, do I need to join this company before filing I-140/I485?",
  "response": "No, you do not necessarily need to join the consulting company before filing the I-140 or I-485 for your Green Card (GC) process. Here\u2019s a breakdown of how it works:\n\n1. **I-140 (Immigrant Petition for Alien Worker)**:\n   - The consulting company (your sponsoring employer) can file the I-140 on your behalf without you having to join them yet. The I-140 is primarily based on the job offer and the company\u2019s willingness to sponsor you for permanent residency.\n   - You can continue working for your current employer (on H-1B or another valid visa) while the I-140 is being processed.\n\n2. **I-485 (Application to Adjust Status)**:\n   - The I-485 can be filed concurrently with the I-140 if your priority date is current (based on the visa bulletin).\n   - You can still remain with your current employer while the I-485 is pending, as long as you maintain valid work authorization (e.g., H-1B).\n   - However, once the I-485 is filed, you may need to join the consulting company when your adjustment of status is approved or when you receive your Green Card, as the Green Card is tied to the job offer from the sponsoring employer (consulting company).\n\n### Key Considerations:\n- **Intent to Join**: When filing the I-140 and I-485, you are indicating your intent to join the consulting company in the future. You don\u2019t need to join them immediately, but you should plan to do so once your Green Card is approved or during the adjustment of status process if required.\n- **Portability Under AC21**: If your I-485 has been pending for more than 180 days, you may be able to change jobs under the American Competitiveness in the Twenty-First Century Act (AC21), as long as the new job is in the same or similar occupational classification as the one listed in your I-140.\n- **H-1B Status**: You can continue working for your current employer on H-1B while the Green Card process is ongoing, as long as your H-1B remains valid.\n\n### Consult an Immigration Attorney:\nIt\u2019s highly recommended to consult an experienced immigration attorney to guide you through the process, especially since Green Card sponsorship through a consulting company can involve complexities related to job duties, location, and employer-employee relationships.\n\nIn summary, you don\u2019t need to join the consulting company before filing the I-140 or I-485, but you will need to work for them eventually, either after your Green Card is approved or during the adjustment of status process.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
